{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37b61ce0-278f-42a7-a7df-f1944cb16d0e","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing heavy tools like PerfView or ETW.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **dotnet-trace** | Quick .NET-specific CPU sampling |\n| **PerfView** | Deep analysis, GC, allocations, ETW events |\n| **dotnet-dump** | If you just need a snapshot of thread stacks |\n\n### Tips for high-CPU scenarios:\n- If the service is **so pegged it's unresponsive**, prefer `dotnet-dump collect -p <PID>` for a quick thread-stack snapshot instead.\n- If you need **native + managed** call stacks (e.g., P/Invoke or OS-level contention), use PerfView with `/ThreadTime` collection.\n- 30 seconds is usually plenty for a CPU-bound issue — the hot path will dominate the trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4baf365-3924-4bad-b34b-b2a35b7f80e7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change task. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"CB13:E9D27:1D7A70C:209F008:6A052567"},"id":"97443aec-1808-4592-a7c7-db321579a0e0","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:29:22.839Z","parentId":"3d5f28dd-b6e1-40f7-8560-5e12dcfaa426"}
